qun 70) -- tPrognostics in Medieval Byzantine Fictional Literature -- tPrognostication in Latin Commentaries on the Book of Revelation -- tPrognostication in Latin Historiography (ca. 400–1300 CE) -- tPrognostication in Medieval Jewish Law and Legal Thought -- tPrognostication in Learned Magic of the Medieval Western Christian World -- tProphecy and Prognostication in Visual Art of the Medieval Western Christian World -- tThe Pseudo-Aristotelian Sirr al-asrār/ Secretum secretorum -- tThe Shoulder-Bone as a Mantic Object -- tSortes -- tThree Images of Celestial Phenomena in Sixteenth-Century German Illustrated Broadsheets -- tTractates on the Division of the Sciences in the Medieval Western Christian World -- tTreatises for Predicting hora mortis in the Medieval Eastern Christian World -- tZījes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwo opposing views of the future in the Middle Ages dominate recent historical scholarship. According to one opinion, medieval societies were expecting the near end of the world and therefore had no concept of the future. According to the other opinion, the expectation of the near end created a drive to change the world for the better and thus for innovation. Close inspection of the history of prognostication reveals the continuous attempts and multifold methods to recognize and interpret God’s will, the prodigies of nature, and the patterns of time. That proves, on the one hand, the constant human uncertainty facing the contingencies of the future. On the other hand, it demonstrates the firm believe during the Middle Ages in a future which could be shaped and even manipulated. The handbook provides the first overview of current historical research on medieval prognostication. It considers the entangled influences and transmissions between Christian, Jewish, Islamic, and non-monotheistic societies during the period from a wide range of perspectives. An international team of 63 renowned authors from about a dozen different academic disciplines contributed to this comprehensive overview.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aHISTORY / Reference.2bisacsh  aMiddle Ages.  aPrognostication.  atransculturality.1 aAvelar de Carvalho, Helena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBar-Asher, Avishai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBar-Levav, Avriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBar-On, Shraga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBihrer, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyle, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandes, Wolfram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnett, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanaris, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaudano, Anne-Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChardonnens, László Sándor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Glen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCortese, Delia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCupane, Carolina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCzock, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemaitre, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubrau, Irmi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDíaz-Fajardo, Montse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngels, David, e